availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: EPT: I know the HW is cach and this doesn't look normal. "na(ch) héinní" is a pronunced variant of "gach aon ní" but unsure how to tag. To be flagged for WG.

There is a mark following this work but it is unclear whether it was intended as a letter form or if the mark arose from something else. If it were intennded as a letter form it may be a repetition of the vertical tilde over the r in the line below, which would render it meaningless nonetheless.

Where an older MS would begin the letters b, l, and h with a wedge at the top left of the letter form, the scribe here has a long stroke sloping downwards to the left of the letter. In this instance the scribe appears to have written that stroke too early, and also appears to have noted lenition on the initial d here. The final product is the letters dul where l has a long stroke trailing horizontally leftwards from the top of the letter form which, it seems, was the scribe's way of altering the text so as not to have an error appear at this point.

There is a mark above the d in this word where it appears that the scribe began to write something but did not complete that mark. Thus, although Greene (1944) writes dho, the present editor does not agree with this reading.
The scribe initally wrote the letter n, then adding the curly descender to render the character a g.

Following "ggedh be" there is a b that is scored out. At the beginning of the next line we find "le" and then a "b" with a suspension stroke. It is the present editor's opinion that either this scribe or the exemplar from which he was working wrote a badly-formed "b", and that the "le b-" should be taken as a repetition of "be" in the previous line.
